<h2>To Robert Cary &amp; Company</h2>

<div class="docbody">
<div class="opener">
<table class="salutationBlock">
        <tr>
		<td class="salutationLeft">Gentn</td>
		<td class="salutationRight">Mount Vernon July 15th 1772</td>
	      </tr>
      </table>
</div>
<p>Inclosed you have mine, Mr &amp; Miss Custiss Invoices for this River<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-09-02-0050-0001-fn-0001" id="GEWN-02-09-02-0050-0001-fn-0001-ptr">1</a>The Goods you will please to forward by the first Vessell for Potomack (which possibly may be Captn Jordan the bearer of this) as there are some articles that will be a good deal wanted especially the Sein, which will be altogether useless to me if I do not get them early in the Spring, or in other words I shall sustain a considerable disappointment, &amp; loss, if they do not get to hand in time.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-09-02-0050-0001-fn-0002" id="GEWN-02-09-02-0050-0001-fn-0002-ptr">2</a> The Invoices for York River must be sent by some other oppertunity as the Steward there (Mr James Hill successor to Mr Valentine) has not yet furnished me with an Acct of the Goods wanting.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-09-02-0050-0001-fn-0003" id="GEWN-02-09-02-0050-0001-fn-0003-ptr">3</a></p>
<p>The Wheat Riddles sent with my last Goods by Mary Vaughan are by no means such as I desired, or such as I can make use of, &amp; therefore I return them<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-09-02-0050-0001-fn-0004" id="GEWN-02-09-02-0050-0001-fn-0004-ptr">4</a>I wanted these Riddles made open enough to let every thing smaller than the broken heads of Wheat &amp; straw throughIn short to have had the Wire 5/8ths of an Inch apart, &amp; thought my directions on this head would have been expressive enough of my meaning to have obtaind my desire. I should still be glad to get such Sieves as these as they are very usefull in taking out the broken heads and Straws before the Wheat is winnowed, but want no others as we have a different method of cleaning Wheat here than that used in England.</p>
<p>Whatever Freight others are charged for the Tobacco Shipped in Peterson last year I shall expect to pay, for Mr Custis &amp; myself but cannot help observing nevertheless that I have
<span class="pb" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="GEWN-02-09-02-pb-0064">[64]</span>
heard of no other Ships going at 10 pr Tonn from this Colony &amp; have good Reasons to believe that they went at a much lower freight from Maryland.</p>
<p>Mr Adam is not yet returned to Virginia, so that I do not know what success he met with in procuring a Gardner for me in ScotlandI am obliged to you however for the trouble you took in endeavouring to get one in London notwithstanding the attempt proovd fruitlessIt was not my Intention to give high Wages, Mr Adam was right therefore in declining the matter when he found they were not to be had upon reasonable terms.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-09-02-0050-0001-fn-0005" id="GEWN-02-09-02-0050-0001-fn-0005-ptr">5</a></p>
<p>Petersons late Sailing will, I fear, proove very detrimental to us, not only in receiving our Goods so late in the Season but on acct of our Tobaccos not getting to an early Market. I remain Gentn Yr Most Obedt Servt</p>
<div class="closer">
<p class="signed">Go: Washington</p>
</div>
</div>
<div class="docback">
<div class="note-source" id="GEWN-02-09-02-0050-0001-sn">

   <p>
<abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Autograph Letter Book ]">ALB</abbr>, <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. Library of Congress, George Washington Papers, Washington, D.C. ]">DLC:GW</span>.
</p>

</div>
<div id="fn" class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-09-02-0050-0001-fn-0001-ptr" id="GEWN-02-09-02-0050-0001-fn-0001">1</a>

   <p>The invoice for the goods that GW ordered for himself is printed here as an enclosure; his invoices ordering goods for his two wards are in <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. Library of Congress, George Washington Papers, Washington, D.C. ]">DLC:GW</span>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-09-02-0050-0001-fn-0002-ptr" id="GEWN-02-09-02-0050-0001-fn-0002">2</a>

   <p>Cary sent most of the listed articles in the <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Trimley</span>, James Page captain, with the invoice dated 29 September. The <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Trimley</span> cleared the Potomac on 30 Dec. 1772. See also <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-09-02-0204-0001" class="document">GW to Cary, 10 July 1773</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-09-02-0050-0001-fn-0003-ptr" id="GEWN-02-09-02-0050-0001-fn-0003">3</a>

   <p>See <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-09-02-0055" class="document">James Hill to GW, 24 July</a>, <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-09-02-0068" class="document">30 Aug.</a>, and <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-09-02-0083" class="document">GW to Cary, 15 Oct. 1772</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-09-02-0050-0001-fn-0004-ptr" id="GEWN-02-09-02-0050-0001-fn-0004">4</a>

   <p>See <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-08-02-0366" class="document">Carys invoice of 3 Dec. 1771</a><span class="choice deletion" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover_choice ] header=[]  body=[ Deleted: ', printed above' &lt;span style='font-size: 90%'&gt;[[2014-11-24]]&lt;/span&gt; ]"><img alt="deletion" src="images/deletion_mark-trans.png" style="border:none;vertical-align: text-bottom; padding-right:2px"/></span>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-09-02-0050-0001-fn-0005-ptr" id="GEWN-02-09-02-0050-0001-fn-0005">5</a>

   <p>Robert Adam was back in Alexandria by 17 Aug. (<span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Donald Jackson and Dorothy Twohig, eds. &lt;i&gt;The Diaries of George Washington&lt;/i&gt;. 6 vols. Charlottesville, Va., 197679. ]"><span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Diaries</span></span>, <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-01-03-02-0002-0017#GEWN-01-03-02-pb-0124" class="document">3:124</a>). Adam was evidently unsuccessful in his quest for a gardener. On 11 Jan. 1773 GW signed an agreement with David Cowan of Fredericksburg to serve as a gardener for a salary of 25 per year, plus lodging, food, and washing. See <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-09-02-0117" class="document">Agreement with David Cowan, 11 Jan. 1773</a><span class="choice deletion" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover_choice ] header=[]  body=[ Deleted: ', printed below' &lt;span style='font-size: 90%'&gt;[[2014-11-25]]&lt;/span&gt; ]"><img alt="deletion" src="images/deletion_mark-trans.png" style="border:none;vertical-align: text-bottom; padding-right:2px"/></span>.</p>

</div>
